org.dblp.util.io

Class DblpXmlByteInputStream

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.io.InputStream
      • org.dblp.util.io.DblpXmlByteInputStream
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Closeable, java.lang.AutoCloseable

    public class DblpXmlByteInputStream
extends java.io.InputStream
    A specialized input stream which is constructed given a number of dblp record keys. The stream then delivers the raw bytes of a dblp.xml file containing only the given records as an InputStream. The record data is accessed via the file system. Only a single file resource will be open at the same time.

    The dblp.dtd will be assumed to be a system resource in the local folder. XML headers will be attached accordingly to match the DTD, i.e.: 

     <?xml version="1.0" encoding="US-ASCII"?>
 <!DOCTYPE dblp SYSTEM "dblp.dtd">
 <dblp>
 ...
 </dblp>
    Example usage of this input stream: 
     DblpXmlByteInputStream in = new DblpXmlByteInputStream("Z:\\dblp\\publ", keys);

 int next = in.read();
 while (next != -1) {
   System.out.write(next);
   next = in.read();
 }

      • read

        public int read()
         throws java.io.IOException
        Reads the next byte of data from the input stream. The value byte is returned as an int in the range 0 to 255. If no byte is available because the end of the stream has been reached, the value -1 is returned.

        Note that if any record given when creating this InputStream cannot be opened for reading, this method throws a FileNotFoundException at the time when the record is reached within the stream.

        Specified by:
        read in class java.io.InputStream
        Returns:
        the next byte of data, or -1 if the end of the stream is reached.
        Throws:
        java.io.FileNotFoundException - as soon as the record specified by the active key cannot be opened for reading.
        java.io.IOException - if a general I/O error occurs.
